## Summary

Implemented the two interaction modes (hold-to-select and click-to-stay) around a pure, fully-tested state machine.

**Core (`Bringr/InteractionMode.swift`, new):**
- `InteractionStateMachine` — a value-type that decides `open`/`select`/`cancel` for both modes. Both modes funnel commits through one `commit(for:)` helper; the *only* difference is which gesture commits — hold-to-select on trigger-**release**, click-to-stay on a **click** (release ignored, menu persists). Re-trigger while open dismisses (toggle parity). (AC1, AC2, AC4)
- `InteractionMode` enum with a single-source-of-truth `defaultsKey` and `current(from:)` reader; default `.holdToSelect`. (AC3)

**Wiring:**
- `RadialMenuController` now delegates all decisions to the machine; reads the persisted mode per summon (`modeProvider`) so a Preferences change takes effect on the next summon. Resolves cursor→slice via `RadialLayout.hitTest` in both global (chord-release) and local (overlay-click) coordinate spaces.
- `MouseChordMonitor` gained an additive `onChordReleased` (the signal hold-mode needs) without touching the pure detector or its 15 tests; `AppDelegate` wires press→`triggerPressed`, release→`triggerReleased`.
- `RadialMenuView` reports click location via a zero-distance drag; menu-bar item forces click-to-stay (a menu click has no "hold").
- `PreferencesView` adds an Interaction section with a radio-group picker bound to `@AppStorage`. (AC3)

**Tests:** 20 new in `InteractionModeTests.swift` (AC5), covering both modes' select/cancel paths, Esc, persistence read/fallback, and re-summon-with-new-mode.

**Gates:** Build SUCCEEDED · SwiftLint `--strict` 0 violations · 88 tests pass (20 new) · app launches stably.

**Scope note:** Live Esc-keypress and click-*outside-the-window* monitors are US-015's explicit charter ("Esc, click-outside, release-in-dead-zone, trigger-loss all cancel cleanly"), so I deliberately left those unwired — the state machine already *handles* `.escape`/`.click(.none)` (tested), and in-window cancels work now. Interactive mode-switching can't be GUI-verified headlessly (no display, can't grant TCC), consistent with US-007.

